Text: when to get birth control

Birth control is super easy to get. I know it sounds like a lot of work but seriously, it’s not that bad. There was a time when you could ONLY get it through your doctor but these days, you can get lots of different kinds online. Yes girl, online! Condoms, the pill, patch, ring, and even the morning after pill are available. You just need to answer a few questions and maybe meet with a doctor online and that’s it! Check out these websites to find online birth control: Prjkt Ruby, The Pill Club, Nurx, and Vagisil.

Menstruation is just a technical way to say period. It’s that time of a month when a woman bleeds for a few days as her body sheds the extra lining her uterus builds up to support pregnancy. If there’s no baby, you’ll get your period. Every month 🙃.
best birth control for cramps

If you suffer from intense period cramps, some kinds of birth control can really help you out. You’ll want to use a hormonal birth control like the pill, ring, shot, patch, implant, or the hormonal IUD. These are known to help reduce cramps and help your period get on track.
period pain

If you suffer from intense period cramps or pain, some kinds of birth control can really help you out. You’ll want to use a hormonal birth control like the pill, ring, shot, patch, implant, or the hormonal IUD. These are known to help reduce cramps and help your period get on track. If your periods are really painful or you are throwing up, definitely talk to a doctor.

What is a cervical biopsy?

A cervical biopsy, or colposcopy, is a procedure that tests for abnormal tissues on the cervix (the small opening between the vagina and uterus). Doctors sometimes order a cervical biopsy after a woman receives an abnormal pap smear. During the biopsy, doctors will take a small piece of tissue from the cervix to test for abnormalities. It can cause some mild pain or discomfort. If you’re sensitive to pain, take a Tylenol before your procedure.

painful period

If you suffer from intense period cramps or pain, some kinds of birth control can really help you out. You’ll want to use a hormonal birth control like the pill, ring, shot, patch, implant, or the hormonal IUD. These are known to help reduce cramps and help your period get on track. If your periods are really painful or you are throwing up, definitely talk to a doctor.

Ovulation is the part of a woman’s monthly cycle where she releases an egg. This is the time of the month that she’s most likely to get pregnant if she has unprotected sex. Choosing the best birth control is a really personal decision. There are 18 different types to choose from and they each work differently. Text: Pregnancy happens when sperm from a guy’s semen connects with a woman’s egg and that egg sticks itself to the side of that woman’s uterus. This is the only way. Grinding, kissing, and even oral sex can’t get you pregnant.
how do you use brith control

Choosing the best birth control is a really personal decision. There are 18 different types to choose from and they each work differently. You have to use a condom every time you have sex, take the pill daily, get a new patch every week, change the ring every month, and the IUD or implant can last for years.
